---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "NEOS ETFs List & Strategy Guide 2026",
  description: "Are high-yield income strategies worth the risk? Unpack the full NEOS ETFs list, how their options-based funds work, and whether they belong in your portfolio.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": meta.title,
      "description": meta.description,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals",
        "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/favicon.ico"
        }
      },
      "datePublished": meta.published,
      "mainEntityOfPage": {
        "@type": "WebPage",
        "@id": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/neos-etfs"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are NEOS ETFs?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "NEOS ETFs are a family of Exchange-Traded Funds focused on income generation. They typically use options strategies, such as covered calls or put spreads, overlaying traditional asset classes to provide high monthly yields to investors."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are the most popular funds on the NEOS ETFs list?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The most popular NEOS ETFs list includes SPYI (S&P 500 High Income ETF), QQQI (Nasdaq 100 High Income ETF), and CSHI (Enhanced Income Cash Alternative ETF). These funds target different asset classes but share a common goal of high yield."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Are NEOS ETFs safe for retirement portfolios?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "While NEOS ETFs can provide significant income, they are generally riskier than standard index funds. Options strategies can cap upside potential during bull markets and may not offer full downside protection during market crashes. They should be considered a component of a diversified portfolio, not a complete retirement strategy."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How often do NEOS ETFs pay dividends?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Most NEOS ETFs are designed to pay out distributions on a monthly basis, making them attractive to investors seeking regular, recurring income."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How are NEOS ETFs taxed?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "NEOS explicitly designs its ETFs to be tax-efficient. They utilize Section 1256 contracts for their options trades, meaning 60% of the gains are treated as long-term capital gains and 40% as short-term, regardless of the holding period."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/neos-etfs"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>{meta.title}</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A beginner-friendly breakdown of options-based income funds and how they generate high monthly yields.</p>
    </div>
    <section class="content-section">
      <p>For investors searching for high yield in a volatile market, the term <strong>NEOS ETFs</strong> has likely crossed your radar. These specialized Exchange-Traded Funds have exploded in popularity because they promise something traditional funds don't: massive monthly payouts driven by sophisticated options strategies.</p>

      <p>But how do these funds actually generate 10% to 12% yields? Are they simply handing you a <a href="/dividend-check">dividend check</a> out of the goodness of their hearts, or is there a catch? In this guide, we will break down exactly how these funds operate, provide a comprehensive <strong>NEOS ETFs list</strong>, and help you determine if these high-income strategies fit into your overall financial plan.</p>

      <h2>The Mechanics of NEOS Options Strategies</h2>
      <p>Traditional index funds buy a basket of stocks and wait for them to go up. A NEOS ETF also buys a basket of stocks (like the S&P 500 or Nasdaq 100), but then adds an "options overlay." Think of options like insurance contracts for stocks. You can buy insurance to protect against a crash, or you can <em>sell</em> insurance to collect premiums. NEOS ETFs generally sell options (like covered calls or credit spreads) to collect premiums. Those collected premiums are then distributed to investors as a high monthly yield.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <h3>Key Concept: Covered Call Strategy</h3>
        <p>A <strong>Covered Call</strong> involves holding a stock while simultaneously selling someone else the right to buy that stock at a higher price later. You keep the cash premium (the yield), but if the stock skyrockets, you cap your potential profit because you must sell it at the agreed-upon price. It's trading upside growth for guaranteed upfront income.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Real-World Example</h2>
      <p>Imagine you own a rental property worth $500,000. It appreciates slowly over time. Now imagine a real estate developer approaches you and says, "I'll pay you $5,000 right now for the <em>option</em> to buy your house for $600,000 next month."</p>

      <p>If the housing market stays flat or drops, the developer walks away, and you keep the $5,000. If the housing market explodes and your house is suddenly worth $800,000, you are still forced to sell it for $600,000. You kept the $5,000 premium, but you missed out on massive capital appreciation. This is the fundamental trade-off of a NEOS ETF: you are sacrificing some upside potential in exchange for high, immediate income.</p>

      <p>This approach stands in stark contrast to heavily concentrated equity plays, such as the <a href="/donald-trump-stock-portfolio">Donald Trump stock portfolio</a>, which relies purely on the volatile price swings of a single asset without the cushion of options premiums.</p>

      <h2>The Complete NEOS ETFs List</h2>
      <p>If you're considering adding these to your portfolio, here is the current <strong>NEOS ETFs list</strong> of their most popular offerings:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>SPYI (NEOS S&P 500 High Income ETF):</strong> Tracks the S&P 500 while selling call options to generate high monthly yield.</li>
        <li><strong>QQQI (NEOS Nasdaq 100 High Income ETF):</strong> Tracks the tech-heavy Nasdaq 100, utilizing a similar options strategy for income.</li>
        <li><strong>CSHI (NEOS Enhanced Income Cash Alternative ETF):</strong> Uses short-term Treasury bills and put-spread options to create a high-yield cash alternative.</li>
        <li><strong>BNDI (NEOS Enhanced Income Aggregate Bond ETF):</strong> Holds standard bonds while using options to boost the overall yield beyond traditional fixed income.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>
      <p>These funds are incredibly useful for retirees or investors who prioritize cash flow over aggressive long-term growth. Because NEOS ETFs utilize Section 1256 contracts for their options trades, their distributions are highly tax-efficient (60% long-term, 40% short-term capital gains). This makes them a powerful tool for generating income in taxable brokerage accounts.</p>

      <p>However, young investors decades away from retirement should be cautious. When you cap your upside potential, you limit the power of compound interest during massive bull markets. A 12% yield is fantastic, but if the underlying index grows by 25% in a year, a standard index fund will drastically outperform the options ETF. Ultimately, NEOS ETFs are income tools, not aggressive growth vehicles.</p>

    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What are NEOS ETFs?</summary>
        <p>NEOS ETFs are a family of Exchange-Traded Funds focused on income generation. They typically use options strategies, such as covered calls or put spreads, overlaying traditional asset classes to provide high monthly yields to investors.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What are the most popular funds on the NEOS ETFs list?</summary>
        <p>The most popular NEOS ETFs list includes SPYI (S&P 500 High Income ETF), QQQI (Nasdaq 100 High Income ETF), and CSHI (Enhanced Income Cash Alternative ETF). These funds target different asset classes but share a common goal of high yield.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are NEOS ETFs safe for retirement portfolios?</summary>
        <p>While NEOS ETFs can provide significant income, they are generally riskier than standard index funds. Options strategies can cap upside potential during bull markets and may not offer full downside protection during market crashes. They should be considered a component of a diversified portfolio, not a complete retirement strategy.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How often do NEOS ETFs pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>Most NEOS ETFs are designed to pay out distributions on a monthly basis, making them attractive to investors seeking regular, recurring income.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How are NEOS ETFs taxed?</summary>
        <p>NEOS explicitly designs its ETFs to be tax-efficient. They utilize Section 1256 contracts for their options trades, meaning 60% of the gains are treated as long-term capital gains and 40% as short-term, regardless of the holding period.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .callout { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-color); padding: 1rem 1.5rem; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }

    .content-section {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      line-height: 1.7;
    }
    .content-section h2 {
      margin-top: 2.5rem;
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
    }
    .content-section p {
      margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
